data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's nothing to migrate on that front. It's already safe for .NET 8.

However, the code has a **closure bug** and could benefit from modernization:

**Closure bug:** The `item` variable is captured by reference. In .NET Framework, all threads may end up processing the *last* item. Fix:

```csharp
foreach (var item in items)
{
    var captured = item; // capture per-iteration
    var t = new Thread(() => Process(captured));
```

> Note: C# 5+ (which .NET 8 uses) scopes `foreach` variables per-iteration, so this bug only applies if you're on C# 4 / .NET Framework 4.0. Still worth being aware of.

**Recommended .NET 8 approach** — replace raw `Thread` with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task`:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

Or with cancellation support (the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`):

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct)
{
    var options = new ParallelOptions { CancellationToken = ct };
    Parallel.ForEach(items, options, item =>
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration guidance for .NET 8:**
| .NET Framework | .NET 8 replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `await` or `Parallel.ForEach` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` |

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 — always use `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation instead.
